      Musk Stuff
   =20
 =20
Last month, Elon Musk committed to fund his $46.5 billion=C2=A0purchase of =
Twitter Inc. with the following sources of money:=09$13 billion of traditio=
nal  leveraged finance debt, borrowed by Twitter at closing.=09$12.5 billio=
n of  margin loans, borrowed by Musk personally, secured by his Tesla Inc. =
stock, at a 20% loan-to-value ratio.[1] So he had to put up $62.5 billion o=
f Tesla stock to secure this $12.5 billion loan.=C2=A0=09$21 billion of  eq=
uity, that is, his own money. He probably did not have $21 billion of cash,=
 so this portion basically meant that he would sell some Tesla stock and us=
e the proceeds to pay for Twitter. And he then=C2=A0 sold about $8.5 billio=
n of Tesla stock, presumably to raise money to fund part of the equity comm=
itment. =E2=80=9CNo further TSLA sales planned after today,=E2=80=9D he  tw=
eeted at the time. He also   sold some Tesla stock last year, and his finan=
ces are not entirely transparent; I suppose it=E2=80=99s possible that he n=
ow has the=C2=A0$21 billion in a checking account.Earlier this month, he an=
nounced a change in the financing:=09$13 billion of LBO debt, same as befor=
e. This was always an   aggressive amount of debt for Musk=E2=80=99s banks =
to lend to Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0something like 8 times expected 2022 earn=
ings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
nd, having gotten them to commit, he=E2=80=99s not going to let that go.=09=
Only $6.25 billion of margin loans, half the original amount. At a 20% LTV =
that would require him to post $31.25 billion of Tesla stock.=09$27.25 bill=
ion of equity. The equity would not be all his own money: He had commitment=
s from other investors to either chip in money or else to roll their existi=
ng Twitter shares into Musk Twitter, totaling about $7.1 billion. But he si=
gned an equity commitment letter for the $27.25 billion: If for some reason=
 those other people flake, he still has to put up the money; as far as Twit=
ter is concerned he=E2=80=99s on the hook for the whole $27.25 billion.So b=
asically he replaced half the margin loan with money from other equity inve=
stors. He still had to pitch in about $20 billion of his own money, that is=
, proceeds from selling Tesla stock.Yesterday he announced another change i=
n the financing:=09Still that $13 billion of good LBO debt.=09Never mind th=
e margin loan; it is gone now.=09$33.5 billion of equity. The entire margin=
 loan has been replaced by an equity commitment.Both last time and this tim=
e, Musk said that he is continuing to=C2=A0talk to potential=C2=A0equity co=
-investors, either to commit more money or to roll their existing Twitter s=
takes into Musk Twitter. (In particular he continues to mention that he=E2=
=80=99s trying to get=C2=A0Twitter founder Jack Dorsey=C2=A0to roll his sha=
res.) So at least $7.1 billion, and possibly $10 billion or $15 billion or =
more, of that $33.5 billion will come from someone other than Musk. But if =
he can=E2=80=99t raise any more equity, he=E2=80=99ll have to come up with =
the $26.4 billion that he hasn=E2=80=99t already syndicated.Why would he sc=
rap the margin loan? Well, it=E2=80=99s important to point out that I don=
=E2=80=99t know anything. But I can do some simple arithmetic:=09If he gets=
 $6.25 billion of margin loan at a 20% LTV, he will need to pledge $31.25 b=
illion of Tesla stock to get the margin loan.=09If he replaces that with $6=
.25 billion of equity, he could sell $8.2 billion of Tesla stock to raise t=
hat money. The top  effective federal capital gains tax rate is 23.8%, and =
the top Texas capital gains tax rate   is zero, so if he sells $8.2 billion=
 of stock that will generate about $6.25 billion of after-tax proceeds.=09$=
8.2 billion is less than $31.25 billion.Tesla=E2=80=99s stock has gone down=
 a lot since the initial announcement of the deal. Musk owns about 163=C2=
=A0million Tesla shares, of which about 92.3 million are pledged to secure=
=C2=A0other=C2=A0loans, leaving him about 70.6=C2=A0million free shares. Wh=
en Musk  first got his margin loan commitment on April 20,[2] those shares =
were worth about $69 billion, more than enough to cover a $12.5 billion mar=
gin loan at a 20% loan-to-value ratio. As of Tuesday=E2=80=99s close, they =
were worth about $44.4 billion, which would support about an $8.9 billion m=
argin loan. That=E2=80=99s cutting it a little close. To get=C2=A0the $6.25=
 billion margin loan at the current=C2=A0low-to-mid-$600s Tesla stock price=
s, Musk would have to pledge most of his remaining shares.A margin loan is =
a way to turn stock into cash at a 20% efficiency rate: Musk can pledge $5 =
of stock to get $1 of margin loan. But just selling=C2=A0the stock turns it=
 into cash at about a 76.2% efficiency rate: He can sell $1 of stock to get=
 back $0.76 of cash (after taxes). Of course if he sells a huge chunk of st=
ock that will drive down the price, but still. If Musk sold all of his rema=
ining unpledged Tesla shares at $500 per share =E2=80=94=C2=A0way below cur=
rent prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0he=E2=80=99d raise about $35 billion, or call it=
 $27 billion after tax, far more than he needs.[3] Whereas pledging all tho=
se shares for a margin loan, even at a $650 stock price, would only raise a=
bout $9 billion.=C2=A0Basically the point here is that Musk has more than e=
nough Tesla stock to=C2=A0sell to pay for Twitter, but only barely enough t=
o=C2=A0borrow against to pay for Twitter. So he has abandoned his initial p=
lans to borrow against his Tesla stock, presumably =E2=80=94=C2=A0who knows=
? =E2=80=94=C2=A0to give him more flexibility to sell it.Or, of course, he =
could sell more of the equity to co-investors, as he is still trying to do.=
 Again, I know nothing, and for a while there was an active business of peo=
ple trying to raise=C2=A0weird funds to buy stakes in Musk Twitter.=C2=A0Bu=
t that business =E2=80=94=C2=A0of syndicating the equity of the deal =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0seems to have gone quiet recently, probably because=C2=A0on May 13=
 Musk tweeted that the deal is =E2=80=9Con hold,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0which does s=
eem like it would make=C2=A0it harder to raise money.Now. As I  said at the=
 time, and as Twitter later  told employees,=C2=A0there is no such thing as=
 =E2=80=9Con hold.=E2=80=9D The process kept moving=C2=A0forward, as you ca=
n tell because a few days later Twitter filed a merger proxy, signed off on=
 by Musk, to get shareholder approval. And now Musk has=C2=A0signed an upda=
ted commitment letter promising to commit even=C2=A0more=C2=A0of his own mo=
ney to the deal. The deal was never =E2=80=9Con hold,=E2=80=9D and Musk=E2=
=80=99s tweeting does not seem to have interrupted the bankers=E2=80=99 and=
 lawyers=E2=80=99 and=C2=A0his own=C2=A0efforts to get the deal closed.When=
 Musk tweeted about the deal being =E2=80=9Ctemporarily on hold pending det=
ails supporting calculation that spam/fake accounts do indeed represent les=
s than 5% of users,=E2=80=9D  I wrote:What is going on here? My=C2=A0initia=
l reaction=C2=A0was that Musk was=C2=A0joking, that this was just a way to =
troll people online. It is, after all, Friday the 13th. =E2=80=9CStill comm=
itted to acquisition,=E2=80=9D he=C2=A0tweeted two hours later.=C2=A0Obviou=
sly this would be a=C2=A0bad=C2=A0joke,=C2=A0insofar as it=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cse=
nt Twitter stock tumbling as much as 25% in premarket trading.=E2=80=9D You=
 are not supposed to say things that aren=E2=80=99t true and that will affe=
ct the stock of a public company that you are trying to buy. That is what i=
s usually called =E2=80=9Csecurities fraud,=E2=80=9D or what I sometimes li=
ke to call =E2=80=9Clite securities fraud.=E2=80=9D Musk has a long history=
 of lite securities fraud: He used to=C2=A0make jokes=C2=A0about Tesla Inc.=
=C2=A0introducing new products=C2=A0or=C2=A0going bankrupt, and he notably=
=C2=A0settled=C2=A0a=C2=A0fraud lawsuit=C2=A0with the U.S. Securities and E=
xchange Commission because he=C2=A0tweeted=C2=A0that he had secured funding=
 to take Tesla private but=C2=A0had not. If he just woke up feeling frisky =
and tweeted a joke about Twitter=E2=80=99s bot accounts, a joke that wiped =
billions of dollars off Twitter=E2=80=99s market capitalization,=C2=A0that =
would be totally unsurprising. Bad! Not really allowed! But very much in ch=
aracter.But then I moved on from that initial reaction. And I, and a lot of=
 people, spent like a week  wondering Will Musk Try To Get Out of the Deal,=
 and Will He Get Away With It, and What Does the Delaware Caselaw on Specif=
ic Performance=C2=A0Look Like, and Could the Number of Bots on Twitter Repr=
esent a Material Adverse Effect, and Will Twitter=E2=80=99s Board Renegotia=
te a Lower Price To Avoid Drawn-Out Litigation With Elon Musk, and other st=
uff that in hindsight was stupid. He really was kidding! He tweeted about t=
he bot thing for a couple of days to troll people,=C2=A0and then he=C2=A0dr=
opped it and continued working diligently to make sure the deal will close.=
[4]=C2=A0And now he has made that closing a bit more certain=C2=A0by replac=
ing the margin loan with a cash equity commitment, effectively promising th=
at even if Tesla=E2=80=99s stock falls further he will still be there with =
the money to buy Twitter. Because he wants to buy Twitter! But he also want=
s to troll people on Twitter.This is very dumb and you really should not tr=
oll people about your plans to buy a $40 billion public company. But Musk d=
oes, and here we are.
