      SEC v. ESG
   =20
 =20
A basic tension in securities regulation is: Would you rather have somethin=
g done=C2=A0badly, or not at all? Or, since everything happens at the margi=
n: Would you rather have=C2=A0more=C2=A0of the thing, at a lower average qu=
ality, or=C2=A0less=C2=A0of it at a higher average quality?This comes up mo=
st classically in disclosure regulations for public companies. Every time t=
he US Securities and Exchange Commission writes new rules saying that publi=
c companies have to disclose more about something, that (1) arguably improv=
es the information available to investors about public companies but (2) ar=
guably makes it harder and more expensive for companies to go public. There=
 are fewer public companies in the US than there used to be, and the ones t=
hat are public tend to be bigger and older. There are lots of reasons for t=
his =E2=80=94=C2=A0including that private markets are deeper and less restr=
icted than they used to be =E2=80=94=C2=A0but people do often argue that it=
 has become more=C2=A0expensive=C2=A0to be public, because there are more d=
etailed disclosure requirements and harsher penalties (lawsuits, etc.) for =
getting that disclosure wrong. Arguably this is good for public investors: =
They get only the most carefully vetted and compliant companies, so their o=
dds of being defrauded are lower. Arguably it is bad: They get only the big=
gest and oldest companies, so their exposure to fast-growing innovative com=
panies is lower.Then there are environmental, social and governance funds. =
You could have two broad ways of thinking about ESG funds:=09We want to enc=
ourage more ESG funds, because it is good to do good things for the=C2=A0en=
vironment and society and governance. The more funds there are that have ES=
G mandates, the more good they will do. If some of those funds are pretty m=
arginal =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they are lazy about ESG, if it is mostly just mar=
keting,=C2=A0if they promise to write ESG reports on all of their investmen=
ts but   only write reports on 75% of their investments =E2=80=94=C2=A0then=
 that doesn=E2=80=99t do that much harm; the point is to encourage lots of =
ESG funds to bloom.=09We want to regulate ESG funds strictly=C2=A0to make s=
ure that they are =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D ESG. We need extensive disclosur=
e rules to make ESG funds explain their strategies in detail, so that inves=
tors can make informed choices about whether those funds=E2=80=99 values ma=
tch their own. If those rules drive out some marginal ESG funds =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0because it is expensive to comply with them, or because the funds are=
 so marginal that they cannot make the required disclosures =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
then that's good, that protects investors.Arguably the first way of thinkin=
g is a socially activist way of thinking (=E2=80=9Cwe want more ESG funds t=
o make the world better, and if some of them=C2=A0lie to investors who care=
s=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0while the second way is a more traditional investor-protec=
tion way of thinking (=E2=80=9Cwe want investors to know what they=E2=80=99=
re getting, and we don=E2=80=99t particularly care which kinds of funds the=
y get=E2=80=9D). Arguably you could hold both views sequentially: Regulate =
ESG lightly while it is in its infancy, to encourage more ESG, but then whe=
n ESG is a dominant mode of investing regulate it more heavily to make sure=
 that it does what it says.Anyway yesterday the SEC proposed two new rules =
for ESG fund disclosure. One is an updated =E2=80=9CNames Rule.=E2=80=9D Si=
nce 2001, the SEC=C2=A0has had a rule saying that the name of your fund has=
 to describe it accurately. If you run the XYZ Bond Fund, it should invest =
in bonds; if you run the ABC Emerging Markets Fund, it should invest in eme=
rging markets. Generally the rule is that 80% of your assets should be in t=
he thing in your name. The proposed new rule would apply this=C2=A0to ESG[5=
]:The proposed amendments to the names rule would address fund names with E=
SG and similar terminology by providing that funds whose names include thes=
e terms are subject to the rule=E2=80=99s 80% investment policy requirement=
, and by defining certain uses of ESG terminology in fund names as material=
ly deceptive and misleading. This would help to prevent potential =E2=80=9C=
greenwashing=E2=80=9D in fund names by requiring a fund=E2=80=99s investmen=
t activity to support the investment focus its name communicates so that in=
vestors will not be deceived or misled by the fund=E2=80=99s name.=C2=A0The=
 details of this strike me as a little strange:The use of ESG or similar te=
rminology in a fund=E2=80=99s name would deceive and mislead investors wher=
e the identified ESG factors do not play a central role in the fund=E2=80=
=99s strategy. Accordingly, we would define the names of =E2=80=9Cintegrati=
on funds=E2=80=9D as materially deceptive or misleading if the name indicat=
es that the fund=E2=80=99s investment decisions incorporate one or more ESG=
 factors. For purposes of this release, an integration fund is a fund that =
considers one or more ESG factors alongside other, non-ESG factors in its i=
nvestment decisions, but such ESG factors are generally no more significant=
 than other factors in the investment selection process, such that ESG fact=
ors may not be determinative in deciding to include or exclude any particul=
ar investment in the portfolio. =E2=80=A6Where a fund considers one or more=
 ESG factors alongside other, non-ESG factors in its investment decisions b=
ut ESG factors are generally no more significant than other factors in the =
investment selection process, such that those ESG factors may not be determ=
inative in deciding to include or exclude any particular investment in the =
portfolio, including ESG terminology in the fund=E2=80=99s name would misle=
ad investors by suggesting that the ESG factors play=C2=A0 a more prominent=
 role.=C2=A0For example, consider a fund with =E2=80=9Csustainable=E2=80=9D=
 in its name that selects investments based on the adviser=E2=80=99s holist=
ic analysis of a company, including conventional financial metrics as well =
as the extent to which the company has good labor and environmental practic=
es. No one factor, including sustainability considerations, is more signifi=
cant than other factors in the investment selection process. As a result, t=
he fund may invest in companies that do not meet the adviser=E2=80=99s own =
criteria for labor or environmental practices, if the adviser determines to=
 make the investment on the basis of other, non-sustainability consideratio=
ns. The fund=E2=80=99s name would be materially deceptive and misleading be=
cause the use of the term =E2=80=9Csustainable=E2=80=9D in its name connote=
s an emphasis on =E2=80=9Csustainability=E2=80=9D considerations that is no=
t consistent with the fund=E2=80=99s investment strategy.I don=E2=80=99t re=
ally know what that means? I do feel like, broadly speaking, most ESG funds=
 try to buy stocks (1) that=C2=A0get good scores on their ESG screens and (=
2) that they think will go up. It depends, of course, and lots of ESG funds=
 are index-y and not making fundamental valuation calls, but if you run an =
actively managed ESG fund it would be a little weird to say =E2=80=9CI thin=
k this company will not emit much carbon because it is going to go bankrupt=
 in a week and shut down entirely, so I should buy a lot of its stock.=E2=
=80=9D[6] Every ESG fund is to some degree trying to balance ESG factors wi=
th buying stocks that will go up. Does that make them all frauds?The other =
proposed rule is much longer and generally calls for ESG funds to make deta=
iled disclosures about their ESG strategies. From the announcement:The prop=
osed amendments seek to categorize certain types of ESG strategies broadly =
and require funds and advisers to provide more specific disclosures in fund=
 prospectuses, annual reports, and adviser brochures based on the ESG strat=
egies they pursue. Funds focused on the consideration of environmental fact=
ors generally would be required to disclose the greenhouse gas emissions as=
sociated with their portfolio investments. Funds claiming to achieve a spec=
ific ESG impact would be required to describe the specific impact(s) they s=
eek to achieve and summarize their progress on achieving those impacts. Fun=
ds that use proxy voting or other engagement with issuers as a significant =
means of implementing their ESG strategy would be required to disclose info=
rmation regarding their voting of proxies on particular ESG-related voting =
matters and information concerning their ESG engagement meetings.Generally =
speaking this is good, if your goal is to protect investors from fake ESG, =
but it does make it harder to be an ESG fund. There are  already complaints=
:The=C2=A0Investment Company Institute, whose members manage more than $40 =
trillion globally, came out Thursday against the SEC=E2=80=99s bid to requi=
re some funds to disclose the aggregated greenhouse gas emissions of compan=
ies they=E2=80=99re invested in. While the ICI signaled support for other a=
spects of the regulator=E2=80=99s proposal, its swift pushback indicates th=
at the industry may be girding for a legal fight.=E2=80=9CThe proposal for =
some funds to disclose emissions related to their holdings seems to be unwo=
rkable =E2=80=94=C2=A0some of the information may not even be publicly avai=
lable,=E2=80=9D said=C2=A0Eric Pan, ICI=E2=80=99s chief executive officer. =
=E2=80=9CAs it considers these proposals, the commission must be attentive =
to the costs of any new requirements =E2=80=94 which will be borne by inves=
tors =E2=80=94=C2=A0as well as the benefits.=E2=80=9DFrom the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 fact sheet for the rule:The proposal generally would require ESG-Focused F=
unds that consider environmental factors in their investment strategies to =
disclose additional information regarding the [greenhouse gas] emissions as=
sociated with their investments. These funds would be required to disclose =
the carbon footprint and the weighted average carbon intensity of their por=
tfolio. The requirements are designed to meet demand from investors seeking=
 environmentally focused fund investments for consistent and comparable qua=
ntitative information regarding the GHG emissions associated with their por=
tfolios and to allow investors to make decisions in line with their own ESG=
 goals and expectations. Funds that disclose that they do not consider GHG =
emissions as part of their ESG strategy would not be required to report thi=
s information.If you are an ESG fund that considers greenhouse gas emission=
s, you have to consider them thoroughly; you have to get the emissions data=
 for your whole portfolio and disclose it in your filings, even if it =E2=
=80=9Cmay not even be publicly available.=E2=80=9D On the one hand this def=
initely helps investors compare the carbon footprints of different ESG fund=
s; on the other hand it does kind of discourage asset managers from launchi=
ng ESG funds focused on greenhouse gas emissions.=C2=A0
