      Who controls a company?
   =20
 =20
Around here we talk sometimes about dumb corporate governance disputes. Not=
, like, =E2=80=9Cthis chief executive officer wants to use the profits from=
 the declining widget business to invest in a pivot to sprockets,=C2=A0but =
an activist investor wants to spend those profits on share buybacks and man=
age the widget decline gracefully,=E2=80=9D but more like =E2=80=9Cthe boar=
d of directors fired this CEO but she has barricaded herself in her office =
and has the passwords for the company=E2=80=99s website and is continuing t=
o claim that she=E2=80=99s the CEO.=E2=80=9D Here=E2=80=99s a good one.Repu=
blic First Bancorp Inc.=C2=A0is a little bank in Pennsylvania that is havin=
g a series of governance fights that I am going to mostly skip over. There =
are two separate activists in the stock, and a board of directors who are f=
ighting with each other; oversimplifying considerably, there is one faction=
 (led by CEO Vernon Hill) that wants to continue an expansion plan (one tha=
t involves =E2=80=9Ca retainer to pay Hill=E2=80=99s wife for architecture =
and interior design work for the bank=E2=80=9D), and another faction (led b=
y founder and former CEO Harry Madonna) that is more sympathetic to the act=
ivists and might want=C2=A0to sell the bank. Everyone is accusing one anoth=
er of various bad things and I will not=C2=A0get into any of it.Instead I w=
ant to talk about the narrow question of who is the chairman of Republic Fi=
rst=E2=80=99s board of directors.=C2=A0Until two weeks ago, Republic First=
=E2=80=99s eight-member board of directors was evenly divided, with four di=
rectors on Hill=E2=80=99s side and four on Madonna=E2=80=99s side, which I =
guess allowed Hill =E2=80=94=C2=A0who was (is?) chairman and CEO =E2=80=94 =
to=C2=A0run the company, since his opponents couldn=E2=80=99t vote him out.=
 But then one of his allies, director Theodore Flocco, died on May 10, leav=
ing the board divided 4 to 3 against him.Two days after Flocco died,=C2=A0M=
adonna =E2=80=9Cpurported to call a special meeting of the Board=E2=80=9D f=
or the next day, apparently to depose Hill as chairman and take over the bo=
ard. Hill concocted a simple strategy to stay in power: He, and his two rem=
aining allies, didn=E2=80=99t dial in to the board meeting. He sent a note =
instead:Directors Hill, Tierney and Spevak object to the calling by Messrs.=
 Madonna, Cohen, and Harris and Ms. Jacobs of a telephonic special meeting =
of the Board of Directors scheduled for May 13 at 10:30 a.m. The rushed dem=
and for a meeting without any agenda and within a day of the passing of Mr.=
 Flocco is both unseemly and improper. Messrs. Hill, Spevak and Tierney wil=
l not attend the meeting. Pursuant to Article II, Section 15 of the Amended=
 and Restated By-Laws of Republic First Bancorp, Inc., in the absence of Me=
ssrs. Hill, Tierney or Spevak, there will not be a quorum of the entire Boa=
rd of Directors, and no business may be transacted.The point of this strate=
gy is that,=C2=A0for the board to meet and conduct business =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
like deposing Hill =E2=80=94=C2=A0it needs to have a quorum. Republic First=
=E2=80=99s bylaws say that a quorum is =E2=80=9Ca majority of the members [=
of] the entire Board of Directors.=E2=80=9D A quorum of an eight-member boa=
rd of directors would be five directors (i.e. one more than 50%). If four d=
irectors do not show up =E2=80=94=C2=A0one because he is dead, the other th=
ree for tactical reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0then there are only four directors =
present, so they arguably cannot conduct business.The other side held the m=
eeting anyway (with four directors) and voted Hill out as chairman, appoint=
ing Madonna interim chairman. (Hill is still CEO.) The company put out an a=
nnouncement saying this, which I guess means that they control the relevant=
 passwords. But then Hill sued; you can read his lawsuit here=C2=A0(I have =
been quoting from it), but the gist of it is that he wants a court to (1) s=
ay that he is still the chairman=C2=A0and (2) prevent the other side from m=
aking other corporate decisions.And that in turn comes down to the question=
 of: How many directors make up =E2=80=9Cthe entire Board of Directors=E2=
=80=9D of Republic First? There are two possibilities:=09If you have an eig=
ht-member board, and one director dies, then there are seven directors. A m=
ajority of seven is four, so four directors constitute a quorum, so the Mad=
onna faction validly met and voted out Hill.=09If you have an eight-member =
board, and one director dies, then there are still eight board seats, but o=
ne of them is empty. You need a majority of the full eight seats =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0five members =E2=80=94=C2=A0to have a quorum, so the four-director me=
eting was not valid, and Hill and his allies can prevent the other side fro=
m doing anything by just not showing up for meetings.I don=E2=80=99t know w=
hich interpretation is right. My point here is really just that corporate l=
aw is weird.
