ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the US</a> than there used to be,=
 and the ones that are public tend to be bigger and older. There are lots o=
f reasons for this =E2=80=94=C2=A0including that private markets are deeper=
 and less restricted than they used to be =E2=80=94=C2=A0but people do ofte=
n argue that it has become more=C2=A0<em>expensive=C2=A0</em>to be public, =
because there are more detailed disclosure requirements and harsher penalti=
es (lawsuits, etc.) for getting that disclosure wrong. Arguably this is goo=
d for public investors: They get only the most carefully vetted and complia=
nt companies, so their odds of being defrauded are lower. Arguably it is ba=
d: They get only the biggest and oldest companies, so their exposure to fas=
t-growing innovative companies is lower.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
en there are environmental, social and governance funds. You could have two=
 broad ways of thinking about ESG funds:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: d=
ecimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">We want to encourage more ESG funds, because it is good to do good t=
hings for the=C2=A0environment and society and governance. The more funds t=
here are that have ESG mandates, the more good they will do. If some of tho=
se funds are pretty marginal =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they are lazy about ESG, if =
