background-color: #ccc;">  only write reports on 75% of their investments</=
a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that doesn=E2=80=99t do that much harm; the point is=
 to encourage lots of ESG funds to bloom.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">We want to regulate ESG funds strictly=C2=A0to make sure that they =
are =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D ESG. We need extensive disclosure rules to mak=
e ESG funds explain their strategies in detail, so that investors can make =
informed choices about whether those funds=E2=80=99 values match their own.=
 If those rules drive out some marginal ESG funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0because it=
 is expensive to comply with them, or because the funds are so marginal tha=
t they cannot make the required disclosures =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that's good=
, that protects investors.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arguably t=
he first way of thinking is a socially activist way of thinking (=E2=80=9Cw=
e want more ESG funds to make the world better, and if some of them=C2=A0li=
e to investors who cares=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0while the second way is a more trad=
itional investor-protection way of thinking (=E2=80=9Cwe want investors to =
know what they=E2=80=99re getting, and we don=E2=80=99t particularly care w=
hich kinds of funds they get=E2=80=9D). Arguably you could hold both views =
sequentially: Regulate ESG lightly while it is in its infancy, to encourage=
 more ESG, but then when ESG is a dominant mode of investing regulate it mo=
re heavily to make sure that it does what it says.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Anyway yesterday the SEC proposed two new rules for ESG fund disclo=
sure. One is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27850=
912.279613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi05MQ/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB592cca1b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">an updated =E2=80=9CNames Rule.=
=E2=80=9D</a> Since 2001, the SEC=C2=A0has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/27850912.279613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZW=
R1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI3MC4zNWQtMQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91040b98" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>had a rule</a> saying that the name of your fund has to describe it accura=
tely. If you run the XYZ Bond Fund, it should invest in bonds; if you run t=
he ABC Emerging Markets Fund, it should invest in emerging markets. General=
ly the rule is that 80% of your assets should be in the thing in your name.=
 The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27850912.2796=
13/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9wcm9wb3NlZC8yMDIyL2ljLTM0NTkzLnBkZg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9128b2b8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">proposed new rule</a> would apply=
 this=C2=A0to ESG[5]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The propo=
sed amendments to the names rule would address fund names with ESG and simi=
lar terminology by providing that funds whose names include these terms are=
 subject to the rule=E2=80=99s 80% investment policy requirement, and by de=
fining certain uses of ESG terminology in fund names as materially deceptiv=
e and misleading. This would help to prevent potential =E2=80=9Cgreenwashin=
g=E2=80=9D in fund names by requiring a fund=E2=80=99s investment activity =
to support the investment focus its name communicates so that investors wil=
l not be deceived or misled by the fund=E2=80=99s name.=C2=A0</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The details of this strike me as a little s=
trange:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The use of ESG or simil=
ar terminology in a fund=E2=80=99s name would deceive and mislead investors=
 where the identified ESG factors do not play a central role in the fund=E2=
=80=99s strategy. Accordingly, we would define the names of =E2=80=9Cintegr=
ation funds=E2=80=9D as materially deceptive or misleading if the name indi=
cates that the fund=E2=80=99s investment decisions incorporate one or more =
ESG factors. For purposes of this release, an integration fund is a fund th=
at considers one or more ESG factors alongside other, non-ESG factors in it=
s investment decisions, but such ESG factors are generally no more signific=
ant than other factors in the investment selection process, such that ESG f=
actors may not be determinative in deciding to include or exclude any parti=
cular investment in the portfolio. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Where a fund considers one or more ESG factors alongside other, non-ESG f=
actors in its investment decisions but ESG factors are generally no more si=
gnificant than other factors in the investment selection process, such that=
 those ESG factors may not be determinative in deciding to include or exclu=
de any particular investment in the portfolio, including ESG terminology in=
 the fund=E2=80=99s name would mislead investors by suggesting that the ESG=
 factors play=C2=A0 a more prominent role.=C2=A0For example, consider a fun=
d with =E2=80=9Csustainable=E2=80=9D in its name that selects investments b=
ased on the adviser=E2=80=99s holistic analysis of a company, including con=
ventional financial metrics as well as the extent to which the company has =
good labor and environmental practices. No one factor, including sustainabi=
lity considerations, is more significant than other factors in the investme=
nt selection process. As a result, the fund may invest in companies that do=
 not meet the adviser=E2=80=99s own criteria for labor or environmental pra=
ctices, if the adviser determines to make the investment on the basis of ot=
her, non-sustainability considerations. The fund=E2=80=99s name would be ma=
terially deceptive and misleading because the use of the term =E2=80=9Csust=
ainable=E2=80=9D in its name connotes an emphasis on =E2=80=9Csustainabilit=
y=E2=80=9D considerations that is not consistent with the fund=E2=80=99s in=
vestment strategy.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=
=99t really know what that means? I do feel like, broadly speaking, most ES=
G funds try to buy stocks (1) that=C2=A0get good scores on their ESG screen=
s and (2) that they think will go up. It depends, of course, and lots of ES=
G funds are index-y and not making fundamental valuation calls, but if you =
run an actively managed ESG fund it would be a little weird to say =E2=80=
=9CI think this company will not emit much carbon because it is going to go=
 bankrupt in a week and shut down entirely, so I should buy a lot of its st=
ock.=E2=80=9D[6] Every ESG fund is to some degree trying to balance ESG fac=
tors with buying stocks that will go up. Does that make them all frauds?</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/27850912.279613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJ=
