</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Around here we talk sometimes about du=
mb corporate governance disputes. Not, like, =E2=80=9Cthis chief executive =
officer wants to use the profits from the declining widget business to inve=
st in a pivot to sprockets,=C2=A0but an activist investor wants to spend th=
ose profits on share buybacks and manage the widget decline gracefully,=E2=
=80=9D but more like =E2=80=9Cthe board of directors fired this CEO but she=
 has barricaded herself in her office and has the passwords for the company=
=E2=80=99s website and is continuing to claim that she=E2=80=99s the CEO.=
=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27850912=
.279613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNjViMzQ2NjYtZGE2NS00ZTA4LTgzMTY=
tMjgzMmI0NTg2MjQw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf37551d1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Here=E2=80=99s=
 a good one</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Republic First Bancorp Inc=
.=C2=A0is a little bank in Pennsylvania that is having a series of governan=
ce fights that I am going to mostly skip over. There are two separate activ=
ists in the stock, and a board of directors who are fighting with each othe=
r; oversimplifying considerably, there is one faction (led by CEO Vernon Hi=
ll) that wants to continue an expansion plan (one that involves =E2=80=9Ca =
retainer to pay Hill=E2=80=99s wife for architecture and interior design wo=
rk for the bank=E2=80=9D), and another faction (led by founder and former C=
EO Harry Madonna) that is more sympathetic to the activists and might want=
=C2=A0to sell the bank. Everyone is accusing one another of various bad thi=
ngs and I will not=C2=A0get into any of it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Instead I want to talk about the narrow question of who is the chairman of=
 Republic First=E2=80=99s board of directors.=C2=A0Until two weeks ago, Rep=
ublic First=E2=80=99s eight-member board of directors was evenly divided, w=
ith four directors on Hill=E2=80=99s side and four on Madonna=E2=80=99s sid=
e, which I guess allowed Hill =E2=80=94=C2=A0who was (is?) chairman and CEO=
 =E2=80=94 to=C2=A0run the company, since his opponents couldn=E2=80=99t vo=
te him out. But then one of his allies, director Theodore Flocco, died on M=
ay 10, leaving the board divided 4 to 3 against him.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Two days after Flocco died,=C2=A0Madonna =E2=80=9Cpurported to ca=
ll a special meeting of the Board=E2=80=9D for the next day, apparently to =
depose Hill as chairman and take over the board. Hill concocted a simple st=
rategy to stay in power: He, and his two remaining allies, didn=E2=80=99t d=
ial in to the board meeting. He sent a note instead:</p><blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Directors Hill, Tierney and Spevak object to the call=
ing by Messrs. Madonna, Cohen, and Harris and Ms. Jacobs of a telephonic sp=
ecial meeting of the Board of Directors scheduled for May 13 at 10:30 a.m. =
The rushed demand for a meeting without any agenda and within a day of the =
passing of Mr. Flocco is both unseemly and improper. Messrs. Hill, Spevak a=
nd Tierney will not attend the meeting. Pursuant to Article II, Section 15 =
of the Amended and Restated By-Laws of Republic First Bancorp, Inc., in the=
 absence of Messrs. Hill, Tierney or Spevak, there will not be a quorum of =
the entire Board of Directors, and no business may be transacted.</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point of this strategy is that,=C2=
=A0for the board to meet and conduct business =E2=80=94=C2=A0like deposing =
Hill =E2=80=94=C2=A0it needs to have a quorum. Republic First=E2=80=99s byl=
aws say that a quorum is =E2=80=9Ca majority of the members [of] the entire=
 Board of Directors.=E2=80=9D A quorum of an eight-member board of director=
s would be five directors (i.e. one more than 50%). If four directors do no=
t show up =E2=80=94=C2=A0one because he is dead, the other three for tactic=
al reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0then there are only four directors present, so th=
ey arguably cannot conduct business.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The ot=
her side held the meeting anyway (with four directors) and voted Hill out a=
s chairman, appointing Madonna interim chairman. (Hill is still CEO.) The c=
ompany <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27850912.27=
9613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzgzNDI4NS8wMDAxND=
M3NzQ5MjIwMTI1MDEvZXhfMzc2MzcwLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB57c8f657" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">put out an announcement saying this</a>, which I guess means that they=
 control the relevant passwords. But then Hill sued; you can <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27850912.279613/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3Nl=
dHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JkX282UlhNaDVXay92MA/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb13c14ac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">read his lawsuit here</a>=C2=A0(=
I have been quoting from it), but the gist of it is that he wants a court t=
o (1) say that he is still the chairman=C2=A0and (2) prevent the other side=
 from making other corporate decisions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And=
 that in turn comes down to the question of: How many directors make up =E2=
=80=9Cthe entire Board of Directors=E2=80=9D of Republic First? There are t=
wo possibilities:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 4=
0px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you have an e=
ight-member board, and one director dies, then there are seven directors. A=
 majority of seven is four, so four directors constitute a quorum, so the M=
adonna faction validly met and voted out Hill.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">If you have an eight-member board, and one director dies, then=
 there are still eight board seats, but one of them is empty. You need a ma=
jority of the full eight seats =E2=80=94=C2=A0five members =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
o have a quorum, so the four-director meeting was not valid, and Hill and h=
is allies can prevent the other side from doing anything by just not showin=
g up for meetings.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t kn=
ow which interpretation is right. My point here is really just that corpora=
te law is weird.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cel=
